# Dark Mode

## How it works

- Light defaults live in `src/styles/tokens/semantic-aliases.css` (`@theme` / semantic `--color-*` variables).
- Dark overrides for the **same** semantic variables live in `src/styles/tokens/dark-mode.css` under an ancestor with class `dark` (typically `html` or the app shell).
- Any component that uses **semantic Tailwind color utilities** (`bg-surface`, `bg-background`, `text-text`, `text-text-muted`, `text-text-disabled`, `border-border`, `bg-interactive-hover`, `bg-interactive-pressed`, `ring-focus`, `text-primary`, etc.) **supports dark mode automatically** — no `dark:` palette utilities required.

## Rules for every new or updated UI component

1. **Semantic colors only** for surfaces, text, borders, and interaction states — same contract as light (see `colors-contract.mdc`). Raw palette utilities break theme consistency in both modes.
2. **Do not** add `dark:bg-gray-*`, `dark:text-gray-*`, or other raw palette `dark:` classes to “approximate” design. If Figma needs a color not covered by existing semantics, **add a semantic token** in `semantic-aliases.css` and **define its `.dark` value** in `dark-mode.css`, then use the new semantic class in the component.
3. **`className` overrides** — when the component sets default width/layout classes, merge with `tailwind-merge` (`twMerge`) so consumers can override without conflicting duplicates.
4. **Verify in both modes** — before finishing, check the component with and without `dark` on the root (or document the need if the shell does not toggle yet).

## App shell

- The product should toggle or set the `dark` class on the appropriate root node. Components stay presentation-only unless explicitly designed to own theme state.
